"Raitsos D.E., Hoteit I., Prihartato P.K., Chronis T., Triantafyllou G., Abualnaja Y.","Abrupt warming of the Red Sea",2011,"Geophysical Research Letters","38","14", L14601,"","",,,10.1029/2011GL047984,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79960480170&partnerID=40&md5=e99a055ac7949622e729eaa9ddc8ab45","Red Sea Research Centre, King Abdullah University for Science and Technology, Thuwal 23955-6900, Saudi Arabia; Hellenic Centre for Marine Research, Institute of Oceanography, GR-190 13 Anavyssos, Greece","Raitsos, D.E., Red Sea Research Centre, King Abdullah University for Science and Technology, Thuwal 23955-6900, Saudi Arabia; Hoteit, I., Red Sea Research Centre, King Abdullah University for Science and Technology, Thuwal 23955-6900, Saudi Arabia; Prihartato, P.K., Red Sea Research Centre, King Abdullah University for Science and Technology, Thuwal 23955-6900, Saudi Arabia; Chronis, T., Hellenic Centre for Marine Research, Institute of Oceanography, GR-190 13 Anavyssos, Greece; Triantafyllou, G., Hellenic Centre for Marine Research, Institute of Oceanography, GR-190 13 Anavyssos, Greece; Abualnaja, Y., Red Sea Research Centre, King Abdullah University for Science and Technology, Thuwal 23955-6900, Saudi Arabia","Coral reef ecosystems, often referred to as ""marine rainforests,"" concentrate the most diverse life in the oceans. Red Sea reef dwellers are adapted in a very warm environment, fact that makes them vulnerable to further and rapid warming. The detection and understanding of abrupt temperature changes is an important task, as ecosystems have more chances to adapt in a slowly rather than in a rapid changing environment. Using satellite derived sea surface and ground based air temperatures, it is shown that the Red Sea is going through an intense warming initiated in the mid-90s, with evidence for an abrupt increase after 1994 (0.7C difference pre and post the shift). The air temperature is found to be a key parameter that influences the Red Sea marine temperature. The comparisons with Northern Hemisphere temperatures revealed that the observed warming is part of global climate change trends. The hitherto results also raise additional questions regarding other broader climatic impacts over the are. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Ecosystems; Reefs; Air temperature; Changing environment; Climatic impact; Coral reef ecosystems; Global climate changes; Ground based; Key parameters; Marine temperatures; Northern Hemispheres; Red sea; Sea surfaces; Temperature changes; Climate change; adaptation; air temperature; climate change; climate effect; coral reef; global climate; ground-based measurement; marine ecosystem; marine environment; Northern Hemisphere; rainforest; satellite imagery; sea surface temperature; vulnerability; Indian Ocean; Red Sea [Indian Ocean]; Anthozoa",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., Marotzke, J., Nordhaus, W.D., Overpeck, J.T., Peteet, D.M., Pietke Jr., R.A., Pierrehumbert, R.T., Wallace, J.M., Abrupt climate change (2003) Science, 299 (5615), pp. 2005-2010. , DOI 10.1126/science.1081056; Astraldi, M., Bianchi, C.N., Gasparini, G.P., Morri, C., Climatic fluctuations, current variability and marine species distribution: A case study in the Ligurian Sea (north-west Mediterranean) (1995) Oceanologica Acta, 18 (2), pp. 139-149; Beaugrand, G., The North Sea regime shift: Evidence, causes, mechanisms and consequences (2004) Progress in Oceanography, 60 (2-4), pp. 245-262. , DOI 10.1016/j.pocean.2004.02.018, PII S0079661104000308; Belkin, I.M., Rapid warming of large marine ecosystems (2009) Prog. Oceanogr., 81, pp. 207-213. , doi:10.1016/j.pocean.2009.04.011; Brohan, P., Kennedy, J.J., Harris, I., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, P.D., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed temperature changes: A new data set from 1850 (2006) Journal of Geophysical Research D: Atmospheres, 111 (12), pp. D12106. , DOI 10.1029/2005JD006548; Cantin, N.E., Cohen, A.L., Karnauskas, K